"Lee H.M., Chang M.B., Chen C.W.","Evaluation of four kinds of nonthermal plasma reactor for abatement of perfluorocompounds",2005,"Journal of Advanced Oxidation Technologies","8","1",,"33","40",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-12444252073&partnerID=40&md5=6fdf80fab833967e51fc5fbe6d1e303b","Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan","Lee, H.M., Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan; Chang, M.B., Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan; Chen, C.W., Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan","Perfluorocompounds (PFCs) are widely used in the semiconductor manufacturing industry as etching gases and chamber cleaning gases. However, PFCs intensely absorb infrared radiation and aggravates global warming consequently. This study applies nonthermal plasma technologies to destroy PFCs including CF4, C2F6, SF6, and NF3. Four kinds of nonthermal plasma reactors including dielectric barrier discharge (DBD), packed-bed plasma (PBP), tandem packed-bed plasma (TPBP), and combined plasma catalysis (CPC) were constructed and tested. Experimental results indicated that higher oxygen and argon contents in the gas streams were beneficial to PFC abatement. For a single CPC reactor, the maximum removal efficiency achieved was 34%. The reduction requirement for semiconductor manufacturing (PFC abatement efficiency &gt; 95%) could be accomplished by combining three CPC reactors in series. The maximum removal efficiency achieved and corresponding energy efficiency were both in the order of CPC &gt; DBD &gt; PBP &gt; TPBP. Endproduct analysis indicated that CF4 was mainly converted into CO2, COF2, and CO. The selectivity of CO2 was in the trend of CPC &gt; PBP &gt; TPBP &gt; DBD, being just reverse to the trend of COF2 selectivity. In general, CPC reactor performs with greater destruction efficiency, better energy utilization, and less hazardous products than the rest three reactors for PFC abatement.","Air pollution control devices (APCDs); Global warming; Greenhouse gases (GHGs); Nonthermgl plasmas (NTPs); Perfluorocompounds (PFCs); Semiconductor manufacturing industry","Nonthermal plasma reactors; Perfluorocompounds (PFC); Plasma reactors; Tandem packed-bed plasma (TPBP); Argon; Catalysis; Chlorofluorocarbons; Energy efficiency; Energy utilization; Hazardous materials; Infrared radiation; Oxidation; Packed beds; Reduction; Semiconductor device manufacture; Plasma devices",,,,,,"Namose, I., (2003) IEEE Trans. Semicond Manurfac., 16 (3), p. 429; Oh, C.H., Lee, N.E., Kim, J.H., Yeom, G.Y., Yoon, S.S., Kwon, T.K., (2003) Thin Solid Films., 435, pp. 264-269; Allgood, C., (1998) Adv. Mater., 10 (15), pp. 1239-1242; Sun, S.Y., Bennett, D., Zazzera, L., Reagen, W., (1998) Semicond Int., 21 (2), pp. 85-86; Chatterjee, R., Karecki, S., Reif, R., Sparks, T., Vartanian, V., Goolsby, B., (2001) J. Electrochem. Soc., 148, pp. G721-G724; Karecki, S., Chatterjee, R., Pruette, L., Reif, R., Sparks, T., Beu, L., Vartanian, V., Novoselov, K., (2001) J. Electrochem. Soc., 148, pp. G141-G146; Cummins, W.R., Dupuis, G., Kesari, S., Miner, D., Trilli, K., Fleming, G., (1997) Semicond Int., 20 (8), pp. 265-272; Tsai, W.T., Chen, H.P., Hsien, W.Y., (2002) J. Loss Prevention Proc. Ind., 75 (2), pp. 65-75; Brown, R.S., Rossin, J.A., Aitchison, K., (2001) Solid State Technol., 44 (7), p. 189; Harz, C.L., Bevan, J.W., Jackson, M.W., Wofforo, B.A., (1998) Environ. Sci. Technol., 32 (5), pp. 682-687; Wofford, B.A., Jackson, M.W., Hartz, C., Bevan, J.W., (1999) Environ Sci. Technol., 33 (11), pp. 1892-1897; Shih, M., Lee, W.J., Tsai, C.H., Tsai, P.J., Chen, C.Y., (2002) J. Air Waste Manage. Assoc., 52 (11), pp. 1274-1280; Baars-Hibbe, L., Sichler, P., Schrader, C., Gessner, C., Gericke, K.H., Buttgenbach, S., (2003) Surf. Coating Technol., 774, pp. 519-523; Sichler, P., Buttge